1
00:00:01,220 --> 00:00:05,720
Heiken Ashi charts are becoming more and more
popular among traders and there are many trading

2
00:00:05,720 --> 00:00:08,340
strategies build around this type of charts.

3
00:00:08,340 --> 00:00:12,700
Heikin Ashi is a modified candlestick charting
technique that rearranges how the price is

4
00:00:12,700 --> 00:00:13,700
displayed.

5
00:00:13,700 --> 00:00:18,060
Basically, Heikin Ashi charts make candlestick
charts more readable for traders who want

6
00:00:18,060 --> 00:00:22,800
to know when to stay in a trade and ride a
strong trend, and when to get out when the

7
00:00:22,800 --> 00:00:24,050
trend weakens.

8
00:00:24,050 --> 00:00:28,359
Although Heikin ashi has many advantages,
a lot of traders prefer to analyze classic

9
00:00:28,359 --> 00:00:29,869
candlestick charts.

10
00:00:29,869 --> 00:00:34,720
But what if you could combine both charts,
in order to have the classic candles and still

11
00:00:34,720 --> 00:00:36,950
be able to plot Heikin-ashi candles?

12
00:00:36,950 --> 00:00:40,160
We can do that by using smoothed Heiken Ashi
candles.

13
00:00:40,160 --> 00:00:44,630
In today’s video, we’ll take a look at
the Heiken Ashi smoothed indicator and I’ll

14
00:00:44,630 --> 00:00:50,090
show you how you can apply this tool and configure
it to your preference.

15
00:00:50,090 --> 00:00:54,080
Before going further, let’s refresh our
memory with how the Heiken Ashi chart plots

16
00:00:54,080 --> 00:01:00,070
prices and how traders use this type of chart
when analyzing the price of an asset.

17
00:01:00,070 --> 00:01:04,290
Candles on traditional Japanese candlestick
charts frequently change their color, which

18
00:01:04,290 --> 00:01:06,370
can make them difficult to read.

19
00:01:06,370 --> 00:01:11,650
On the other hand, candles on the Heikin Ashi
chart display more consecutive colored candles,

20
00:01:11,650 --> 00:01:14,930
helping traders to identify past price movements
more easily.

21
00:01:14,930 --> 00:01:20,000
You’ll notice that Heikin Ashi charts have
a tendency for its candles to stay green during

22
00:01:20,000 --> 00:01:23,140
an uptrend and stay red during a downtrend.

23
00:01:23,140 --> 00:01:28,140
This is in contrast to traditional Japanese
candlesticks that alternate color even if

24
00:01:28,140 --> 00:01:31,260
the price is moving strongly in one direction.

25
00:01:31,260 --> 00:01:36,320
Heikin Ashi chart is much smoother looking
in terms of price action.

26
00:01:36,320 --> 00:01:40,909
This is why many traders prefer to use the
Heikin Ashi candles since it reduces the noise

27
00:01:40,909 --> 00:01:44,920
on the chart, and allows them to analyze trends
more clearly.

28
00:01:44,920 --> 00:01:49,480
What makes Heikin Ashi different from a traditional
Japanese candlestick chart is how the price

29
00:01:49,480 --> 00:01:52,670
is displayed in terms of the open and the
close.

30
00:01:52,670 --> 00:01:57,170
If you look closely at the Heikin Ashi chart,
you’ll notice that each of the Heikin Ashi

31
00:01:57,170 --> 00:02:02,070
candlesticks start from the MIDDLE of the
candlestick before it, and not from the level

32
00:02:02,070 --> 00:02:06,170
where the previous candlestick had closed.

33
00:02:06,170 --> 00:02:12,319
While Japanese candlesticks require many definitions
and flexible rules for most patterns, a heikin-ashi

34
00:02:12,319 --> 00:02:14,790
chart works with only the five simple rules.

35
00:02:14,790 --> 00:02:15,790
1.

36
00:02:15,790 --> 00:02:21,170
A sequence of green bodies identifies an uptrend,
while a sequence of red bodies identifies

37
00:02:21,170 --> 00:02:22,170
a downtrend.

38
00:02:22,170 --> 00:02:23,170
2.

39
00:02:23,170 --> 00:02:27,730
The uptrend gets stronger with longer green
bodies and no lower shadows.

40
00:02:27,730 --> 00:02:32,280
The downtrend gets stronger with longer red
bodies and no upper shadows.

41
00:02:32,280 --> 00:02:33,280
3.

42
00:02:33,280 --> 00:02:38,150
The trend gets weaker with smaller bodies
and with the emergence of lower and upper

43
00:02:38,150 --> 00:02:39,150
shadows.

44
00:02:39,150 --> 00:02:40,150
4.

45
00:02:40,150 --> 00:02:44,810
A consolidation is revealed when you spot
a series of smaller bodies with both upper

46
00:02:44,810 --> 00:02:46,040
and lower shadows.

47
00:02:46,040 --> 00:02:47,090
5.

48
00:02:47,090 --> 00:02:52,520
A trend reversal could follow when you spot
multiple candles with small bodies and long

49
00:02:52,520 --> 00:02:57,580
upper and lower shadows (doji-like candle)
or a sudden color change.

50
00:02:57,580 --> 00:03:02,440
Just like any other tool used for technical
analysis, Heikin Ashi is useful but it does

51
00:03:02,440 --> 00:03:05,250
have some weaknesses or limitations.

52
00:03:05,250 --> 00:03:09,730
While the traditional Japanese candlesticks
are derived from the actual prices, Heikin

53
00:03:09,730 --> 00:03:11,569
Ashi candlesticks are NOT.

54
00:03:11,569 --> 00:03:16,010
Because the Heikin Ashi candlesticks are averaged,
they do NOT show the exact open and close

55
00:03:16,010 --> 00:03:18,440
prices for a particular time period.

56
00:03:18,440 --> 00:03:22,200
Heikin Ashi charts obscure actual price information.

57
00:03:22,200 --> 00:03:26,270
The closing price is considered important
for many traders, but the actual closing price

58
00:03:26,270 --> 00:03:28,860
is NOT displayed on a Heikin Ashi candlestick.

59
00:03:28,860 --> 00:03:33,360
But we can fix this problem by using the smoothed
Heiken Ashi.

60
00:03:33,360 --> 00:03:39,820
Smoothed Heiken Ashi is a modified version
of the regular Heiken Ashi candlestick charts.

61
00:03:39,820 --> 00:03:44,440
While you can typically use the regular Heiken
Ashi chart all by itself, the Heiken Ashi

62
00:03:44,440 --> 00:03:49,459
smoothed indicator is used as an overlay on
the regular candlestick chart.

63
00:03:49,459 --> 00:03:53,319
If you have a Tradingview account, this is
the exact version I use.

64
00:03:53,319 --> 00:03:57,709
As you can see, you’ll get a better perspective
of the markets.

65
00:03:57,709 --> 00:04:02,270
You can see the regular candlestick chart
alongside the Heiken Ashi smoothed indicator.

66
00:04:02,270 --> 00:04:06,659
This is not possible if you use the regular
Heiken Ashi chart.

67
00:04:06,659 --> 00:04:12,190
The main difference between the regular Heiken
Ashi and the Heiken Ashi smoothed indicator

68
00:04:12,190 --> 00:04:16,500
is that the second one plots the Heiken Ashi
candlesticks as a moving average.

69
00:04:16,500 --> 00:04:20,530
The general rule of thumb is that the markets
are in an uptrend when the smoothed Heiken

70
00:04:20,530 --> 00:04:25,460
Ashi indicator is bullish or green, and the
markets are in a downtrend when the smoothed

71
00:04:25,460 --> 00:04:28,550
Heiken Ashi indicator is bearish or red.

72
00:04:28,550 --> 00:04:32,120
Smoothed Heiken Ashi is a trend following
indicator.

73
00:04:32,120 --> 00:04:34,850
In uptrends, price tends to stay above it.

74
00:04:34,850 --> 00:04:38,889
In downtrends, price typically stays below
the Smoothed Heiken Ashi.

75
00:04:38,889 --> 00:04:44,440
The first possibility of a change in trend
is when price crosses through the indicator.

76
00:04:44,440 --> 00:04:49,930
Downtrends start to reverse when prices cross
back up and through the smoothed HA, while

77
00:04:49,930 --> 00:04:56,229
uptrends show signs of reversal when price
falls through the smoothed HA, below it.

78
00:04:56,229 --> 00:05:00,440
The settings for the smoothed Heiken Ashi
indicator are very simple.

79
00:05:00,440 --> 00:05:04,080
You can set the values of the two moving averages
that are used.

80
00:05:04,080 --> 00:05:08,610
Depending on your trading style, scalping,
day trading or swing trading, you can change

81
00:05:08,610 --> 00:05:11,310
the value of the indicator to suit your trading
needs.

82
00:05:11,310 --> 00:05:17,650
Here are several settings you could try:
First one: 5 period Smoothed Heiken Ashi

83
00:05:17,650 --> 00:05:23,520
This is suited to scalping techiques, tracking
the strong momentum and the trend in the short

84
00:05:23,520 --> 00:05:24,520
term.

85
00:05:24,520 --> 00:05:28,370
The 5 period Smoothed Heiken Ashi acts as
support in the strongest trends.

86
00:05:28,370 --> 00:05:32,990
This line is best used in low volatility trends
with strong momentum.

87
00:05:32,990 --> 00:05:36,009
You can also use it as a trailing stop.

88
00:05:36,009 --> 00:05:41,410
10 period Smoothed Heiken Ashi, which is the
default value, is a great method to keep you

89
00:05:41,410 --> 00:05:43,590
on the right side of the major market trend.

90
00:05:43,590 --> 00:05:49,380
It is usually the first line to be lost before
any real trouble begins, meaning any reversals

91
00:05:49,380 --> 00:05:50,960
in current trend.

92
00:05:50,960 --> 00:05:56,330
From my backtesting, it can be used as a standalone
signal in some stocks and markets that tend

93
00:05:56,330 --> 00:06:00,490
to trend strongly in one direction for long
periods.

94
00:06:00,490 --> 00:06:05,050
20 period Smoothed Heiken Ashi acts like an
intermediate term moving average.

95
00:06:05,050 --> 00:06:09,090
It is generally the last line of support in
a volatile uptrend.

96
00:06:09,090 --> 00:06:13,680
To me, it is the reversion to the mean in
a market when it finally pulls back after

97
00:06:13,680 --> 00:06:15,520
an extended trend.

98
00:06:15,520 --> 00:06:20,789
50 period Smoothed Heiken Ashi is the line
that strong leading stocks typically pull

99
00:06:20,789 --> 00:06:21,800
back to.

100
00:06:21,800 --> 00:06:25,580
This is usually the main support level for
strong uptrends.

101
00:06:25,580 --> 00:06:29,490
Most bull markets and uptrends will usually
pull back to this level.

102
00:06:29,490 --> 00:06:35,360
From my backtesting, the 50 period Smoothed
Heiken Ashi is generally a great “Buy the

103
00:06:35,360 --> 00:06:36,830
dip” level.

104
00:06:36,830 --> 00:06:41,630
If you enjoy swing trading or position trading,
you could use the 100 period Smoothed Heiken

105
00:06:41,630 --> 00:06:44,389
Ashi, which indicate long term direction.

106
00:06:44,389 --> 00:06:47,210
This is the deeper pullback level in bull
markets and uptrends.

107
00:06:47,210 --> 00:06:51,740
It usually presents a great risk/reward ratio
in bull markets.

108
00:06:51,740 --> 00:06:57,410
Now, how to Use Smoothed Heiken Ashi
There are 3 main ways in which you can use

109
00:06:57,410 --> 00:06:59,900
the Smoothed Heiken Ashi:
• To determine the direction of the trend

110
00:06:59,900 --> 00:07:05,370
• To determine support and resistance levels
• Using multiple Smoothed Heiken Ashi for

111
00:07:05,370 --> 00:07:07,400
long- and short-term market trends

112
00:07:07,400 --> 00:07:09,259
1.

113
00:07:09,259 --> 00:07:12,009
First approach is to determine the direction
of the trend

114
00:07:12,009 --> 00:07:17,009
When prices are trending higher, the Smoothed
Heiken Ashi will adjust by also moving higher

115
00:07:17,009 --> 00:07:19,110
to reflect the increasing prices.

116
00:07:19,110 --> 00:07:23,850
This could be explained as a bullish signal,
where traders may prefer buying opportunities.

117
00:07:23,850 --> 00:07:27,889
The opposite would be true if the price was
consistently trading below the Smoothed Heiken

118
00:07:27,889 --> 00:07:32,990
Ashi indicator, where traders would then prefer
selling opportunities due to the market signaling

119
00:07:32,990 --> 00:07:34,830
a downward trend.

120
00:07:34,830 --> 00:07:35,830
2.

121
00:07:35,830 --> 00:07:39,850
Second approach is using Smoothed Heiken Ashi
for support and resistance levels

122
00:07:39,850 --> 00:07:44,430
If you see the Smoothed Heiken Ashi trending
higher, you could enter the market on a retest

123
00:07:44,430 --> 00:07:46,300
of the Smoothed Heiken Ashi.

124
00:07:46,300 --> 00:07:50,669
Likewise, when you are long in an uptrend
market, then the Smoothed Heiken Ashi can

125
00:07:50,669 --> 00:07:52,610
be used as a stop loss level.

126
00:07:52,610 --> 00:07:55,610
The opposite is true for down trends.

127
00:07:55,610 --> 00:07:59,960
In this chart you can see several examples
of how the Smoothed Heiken Ashi can be used

128
00:07:59,960 --> 00:08:02,810
as powerful level of support or resistance.

129
00:08:02,810 --> 00:08:03,810
3.

130
00:08:03,810 --> 00:08:08,180
Third approach is making use of multiple Smoothed
Heiken Ashi

131
00:08:08,180 --> 00:08:13,780
This allows traders to simultaneously assess
the short and long-term trends in the market.

132
00:08:13,780 --> 00:08:18,509
As price crosses above or below these plotted
levels on the graph it can be explained as

133
00:08:18,509 --> 00:08:22,190
either strength or weakness for the asset
you are trading.

134
00:08:22,190 --> 00:08:27,460
This method of using more than one Smoothed
Heiken Ashi can be extremely useful in trending

135
00:08:27,460 --> 00:08:28,460
markets.

136
00:08:28,460 --> 00:08:34,699
Now, very important: when making use of multiple
Smoothed Heiken Ashi, you might have the idea

137
00:08:34,699 --> 00:08:36,819
to trade when the lines will cross.

138
00:08:36,819 --> 00:08:42,099
A bullish cross is identified when the short-term
Smoothed Heiken Ashi crosses above the long-term

139
00:08:42,099 --> 00:08:46,489
Smoothed Heiken Ashi, while a bearish cross
represents the short-term Smoothed Heiken

140
00:08:46,489 --> 00:08:49,790
Ashi crossing below the long-term Smoothed
Heiken Ashi.

141
00:08:49,790 --> 00:08:52,189
Don’t use this strategy.

142
00:08:52,189 --> 00:08:56,619
Heiken Ashi is considered a lagging indicator
that not only dismisses useless signals to

143
00:08:56,619 --> 00:09:00,980
open the trade but also provide you with a
late signal for closing the trade.

144
00:09:00,980 --> 00:09:06,369
Attempting to build a crossover strategy with
2 Smoothed Heikin Ashi lines is very bad idea.

145
00:09:06,369 --> 00:09:10,600
If you don’t want to see the market slowly
destroying your profit as the trend you are

146
00:09:10,600 --> 00:09:15,689
trying to trade has already changed, I advise
you to use multiple Smoothed Heikin Ashi lines

147
00:09:15,689 --> 00:09:21,529
only for dynamic support and resistance levels,
and not for crossover signals.

148
00:09:21,529 --> 00:09:25,130
Every Heikin Ashi trading system should include
price action rules:

149
00:09:25,130 --> 00:09:29,420
• So look for Support and Resistance levels
• look for chart patterns for potential

150
00:09:29,420 --> 00:09:30,480
breakouts.

151
00:09:30,480 --> 00:09:34,529
• And try to enter into emerging trends
and exit on slowing trends.

152
00:09:34,529 --> 00:09:39,819
Also, as you are able to see the classic candlesticks
you can combine classic price action with

153
00:09:39,819 --> 00:09:41,379
Smoothed Heikin Ashi.

154
00:09:41,379 --> 00:09:46,619
You will able to identify a pin bar, an engulfing
candle or a reversal pattern and at the same

155
00:09:46,619 --> 00:09:49,480
time, knowing what Heikin Ashi are indicating.

156
00:09:49,480 --> 00:09:55,509
With classic candlesticks, an engulfing candlestick
pattern at a support level can be a nice starting

157
00:09:55,509 --> 00:09:59,119
signal, a decent entry into a beginning upward
movement.

158
00:09:59,119 --> 00:10:02,269
Nevertheless, there is room for misinterpretation.

159
00:10:02,269 --> 00:10:07,399
With additional smoothed Heikin Ashi candles
on the same chart, you can mitigate this danger

160
00:10:07,399 --> 00:10:13,660
of misinterpretation and can help you to judge
a trend more clearly in combination with classic

161
00:10:13,660 --> 00:10:14,660
candlesticks.

162
00:10:14,660 --> 00:10:19,499
That’s why it’s better to use both candle
types on the same chart.

163
00:10:19,499 --> 00:10:23,819
Despite the simplicity of the Heikin Ashi
approach, you must be aware that Heikin Ashi

164
00:10:23,819 --> 00:10:27,739
candles, unlike classic candlesticks, are
in fact indicators.

165
00:10:27,739 --> 00:10:31,860
This is due to the construction of Heikin
Ashi candles, in which the current and previous

166
00:10:31,860 --> 00:10:33,550
periods are always considered.

167
00:10:33,550 --> 00:10:37,259
So the Heikin Ashi Candles are not the ultimate
trading instrument.

168
00:10:37,259 --> 00:10:41,819
That’s why the combination between classic
candlesticks and Heikin Ashi represents a

169
00:10:41,819 --> 00:10:44,110
better and safer approach to trade.

170
00:10:44,110 --> 00:10:49,160
You analyze the markets on the classic candlestick
chart, and you apply the Smoothed Heikin Ashi

171
00:10:49,160 --> 00:10:52,769
to filter against false signals and background
noises.

172
00:10:52,769 --> 00:10:56,569
